Here's the recommended approach using **CommunityToolkit.Mvvm** source generators:

**ViewModel:**

```csharp
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.ComponentModel;
using CommunityToolkit.Mvvm.Input;

public partial class ProductDetailViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private string _name = string.Empty;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private decimal _price;

    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool _isAvailable;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task LoadAsync()
    {
        // Simulate async fetch
        var product = await ProductService.GetProductAsync();
        Name = product.Name;
        Price = product.Price;
        IsAvailable = product.IsAvailable;
    }
}
```

The source generator creates public `Name`, `Price`, `IsAvailable` properties (with `PropertyChanged` notifications) and a `LoadCommand` automatically.

**XAML with compiled bindings:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns:vm="clr-namespace:MyApp.ViewModels"
             x:DataType="vm:ProductDetailViewModel">
    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="16" Spacing="8">
        <Label Text="{Binding Name}" FontSize="24" />
        <Label Text="{Binding Price, StringFormat='Price: {0:C2}'}" />
        <Label Text="{Binding IsAvailable, StringFormat='Available: {0}'}" />
        <Button Text="Load" Command="{Binding LoadCommand}" />
    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```

**Key points:**
- `x:DataType` at the page root enables compiled bindings (8–20× faster, AOT-safe).
- `[ObservableProperty]` generates the property + change notification boilerplate.
- `[RelayCommand]` on `LoadAsync` generates `LoadCommand` (an `IAsyncRelayCommand` that disables the button while running).
- `PropertyChanged` is auto-marshalled to the UI thread, so assigning from an async context is safe.

Add `<WarningsAsErrors>XC0022;XC0025</WarningsAsErrors>` to your `.csproj` to catch binding errors at build time.
